> Have an attorney review before publishing.

## What this covers

"[Marks]" means the name **"[Project Name]"**, the **[Project Name] logo**, and
[any other names/logos]. The software is licensed under [SPDX-ID] (see `LICENSE`),
but the Marks are **not** licensed with the code — they are owned by
[Holder/Entity].

## Uses that are always allowed (no permission needed)

- Referring to the project truthfully ("works with [Project Name]",
  "compatible with [Project Name]", "a plugin for [Project Name]").
- Non-commercial, educational, and community use that does not imply endorsement.
- Stating that your fork or distribution is **based on / derived from**
  [Project Name] (e.g. "Powered by [Project Name]"), provided you do not present
  it as the official project.

## Uses that require written permission

- Using the Marks as (or within) the **name of your own product, company, or
  service**, especially a commercial or hosted one.
- Using the **logo** in a modified form, or in a way that suggests official
  status, sponsorship, or endorsement.
- Domain names, app names, or social handles that could be mistaken for the
  official project.

## The cardinal rule

**Your use must not be misleading or imply that [Holder] endorses, sponsors, or
is affiliated with you** unless we have agreed to that in writing.

## Forks and redistributions

You may distribute modified versions under [SPDX-ID], but if your version differs
materially from the official release, please **rename it** so users are not
confused about which is the official [Project Name].

